{
  "texts": [
    "The detailed outcomes of the studies are presented in Fig. 7.Fig.",
    "3 The effect of different embedding dimensions on the AUC and AUPR of NAGTLDA Fig. 4 The effect of different maximal smoothing steps on the AUC and AUPR of NAGTLDAWe can observe that when the ratio = 1:1, indicating a balanced ratio of positive and negative samples, the AUC and AUPR values are the highest at 0.9531 and 0.9537, respectively, but the corresponding accuracy is the lowest.",
    "When the ratio = 1:5, the AUC and AUPR values are slightly lower than those of the ratio = 1:1, but the accuracy is slightly higher.",
    "When the ratio = 1:10, the AUC value is the lowest, but the accuracy is higher than the previous ratios.",
    "When the ratio is set to random, the AUC value is ranked third, and the AUPR value is the lowest, but the accuracy is the highest at 0.9783."
  ]
}